<paragraph blockId="3.[159,762,1298,1617]" box="[197,744,1593,1617]" pageId="3" pageNumber="343">Etymology — Named for its slender idiosoma.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[159,762,1644,1949]" lastBlockId="3.[826,1429,1298,1497]" pageId="3" pageNumber="343">
Remarks — The lack of one acetabulum is a phenomenon observed in other aturid genera as well, e.g. in 
<taxonomicName box="[248,333,1714,1738]" class="Arachnida" family="Aturidae" genus="Javalbia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="3" pageNumber="343" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[248,333,1714,1738]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="343">Javalbia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Smit H. &amp; Pesi'c V." box="[349,594,1714,1738]" pageId="3" pageNumber="343" pagination="1 - 71" refId="ref9616" refString="Smit H., Pesi'c V. 2014 - Water mites from Mount Kinabalu and the Crocker Range, Borneo, Malaysia (Acari: Hydrachnidia), with the description of 34 new species - Zootaxa, 3876: 1 - 71. doi: 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3876.1.1" type="journal article" year="2014">Smit and Peši´c 2014</bibRefCitation>
). However, it may be expected that normally three pairs will be present in a configuration as shown in the right side of the genital field. Due to its small size and the configuration of the acetabula, the new species is most close to 
<emphasis box="[261,469,1889,1913]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="343">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Szalay" authorityYear="1944" box="[261,363,1889,1913]" class="Arachnida" family="Aturidae" genus="Albaxona" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="3" pageNumber="343" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Albaxona</taxonomicName>
hexapora
</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Viets K." box="[488,619,1889,1913]" pageId="3" pageNumber="343" pagination="1 - 113" refId="ref9772" refString="Viets K. 1935 - Die Wassermilben von Sumatra, Java und Bali nach den Ergebnissen der Deutschen Limnologischen Sunda-Expedition - Arch. Hydrobiol., Suppl. 13, Trop. Binnengewasser, 5 (3): 484 - 594, 5 (4): 595 - 738, Suppl. 14, Trop. Binnengewasser, 6 (1): 1 - 113." type="journal article" year="1935">Viets, 1935</bibRefCitation>
) from Java. However, the new species is more slender, L/W of the idiosoma is 
<quantity box="[1019,1098,1298,1322]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.2004" pageId="3" pageNumber="343" unit="in" value="1.26">1,26 in</quantity>
<emphasis box="[1108,1239,1298,1322]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="343">A. hexapora</emphasis>
and 
<quantity box="[1303,1382,1298,1322]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.3528" pageId="3" pageNumber="343" unit="in" value="1.32">1,32 in</quantity>
the new species. 
<taxonomicName authority="Gledhill and Wiles, 1997" authorityName="Gledhill and Wiles" authorityYear="1997" class="Arachnida" family="Aturidae" genus="Albaxona" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="3" pageNumber="343" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kurtvietsi">
<emphasis box="[983,1195,1333,1357]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="343">Albaxona kurtvietsi</emphasis>
Gledhill and Wiles, 1997
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry box="[953,1067,1368,1392]" name="Sri Lanka" pageId="3" pageNumber="343">Sri Lanka</collectingCountry>
is another small species. This species has the acetabula lying in a line and the postocularia are lying closer to dgl-1 compared to the new species.
</paragraph>
